INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0947f03d-c930-4691-af36-bee58ae6696c',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Terraform Workspaces — Managing dev/staging/prod Without Duplicating Code$escape$,
  $escape$Terraform workspaces let you maintain isolated state files for the same configuration. Run `terraform workspace new staging` and you get a separate `terraform.tfstate` for that environment — no separate directories, no code duplication. The current workspace is exposed via `terraform.workspace`, so you can branch resource sizing and naming inline.

The real power is combining workspaces with a `locals` map: define per-environment values keyed by workspace name, then reference `local.env_config` throughout. This keeps all environment differences in one block, not scattered across the codebase.

One hard rule: workspaces share the same backend bucket. Use key prefixes (`env:/<workspace>/terraform.tfstate` is the S3 default) and restrict prod workspace access via IAM policies or Terraform Cloud workspace permissions — never let a dev pipeline touch prod state. Workspaces shine for infrastructure that's structurally identical across environments. For environments with fundamentally different topology (e.g., prod has a multi-region setup dev lacks), separate root modules are the better call.$escape$,
  $escape$locals {
  env_config = {
    dev     = { instance_type = "t3.micro", min_size = 1 }
    staging = { instance_type = "t3.small", min_size = 2 }
    prod    = { instance_type = "t3.large", min_size = 4 }
  }
  cfg = local.env_config[terraform.workspace]
}

resource "aws_autoscaling_group" "app" {
  min_size          = local.cfg.min_size
  launch_template {
    id = aws_launch_template.app.id
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
