INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '962ed27a-60a9-4131-9125-1c64d2680ab6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Terraform Destroy Safety — Lifecycle Rules That Prevent Accidental Deletion$escape$,
  $escape$Terraform's `terraform destroy` or a misconfigured `terraform apply` can obliterate production infrastructure in seconds. Three lifecycle meta-arguments are your primary defense.

`prevent_destroy = true` causes Terraform to hard-error if any plan includes destroying that resource — it won't even generate a destroy plan. Use it on stateful resources: RDS instances, S3 buckets, Kubernetes clusters.

`ignore_changes` prevents Terraform from treating external mutations as drift, stopping it from destroying and recreating resources that get modified outside IaC (e.g., auto-scaling adjustments, manual AMI updates).

For entire workspaces, combine `prevent_destroy` with a `-target` discipline: never run `terraform destroy` without `-target` in production. Add a CI guard using `terraform plan -detailed-exitcode` and fail the pipeline if the plan contains any `destroy` actions against tagged critical resources.

In Terraform Cloud/Enterprise, use run policies (Sentinel or OPA) to block plans where `resource_changes[*].change.actions` contains `"delete"` on resources tagged `environment=production`. This shifts the safety left into policy-as-code rather than relying on human review.$escape$,
  $escape$resource "aws_db_instance" "primary" {
  identifier        = "prod-postgres"
  instance_class    = "db.t3.medium"
  engine            = "postgres"
  allocated_storage = 100

  lifecycle {
    prevent_destroy = true
    ignore_changes  = [engine_version, snapshot_identifier]
  }
}

# CI gate: fail pipeline if destroy actions detected on critical resources
# terraform plan -out=tfplan && terraform show -json tfplan | \
#   jq '.resource_changes[] | select(.change.actions[] == "delete")' | grep -q . && exit 1$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
